Overview
Overview
ONDC API contract maps various use cases to APIs and ensures interoperability as follows:
by defining the set of attributes that need to be exchanged between the BNP & SNP, to initiate & complete a transaction;
clearly defining the single source of truth for each attribute key and thereby establishing mutability & immutability of these keys on behalf of NPs at each end of the transaction;
This document is structured as follows:
different pre-order & post-order APIs, for thebaseline requirements, along with sample json payload;
transaction flows for different "enhanced" use cases;
expected behaviour of APIs for different use cases;
All attributes, defined in this API contract, are mandatory, unless explicitly mentioned otherwise. Additionally, NPs may send optional attributes as per the swagger spechere. Participants may validate the request & response payloads, based on attributes as defined, and respond appropriately;
All participants are required to ensure full compliance with this API contract on the live ONDC network.
Construct of APIs & transaction trail
Construct of APIs & transaction trail
All APIs follow the same construct and include:
Context- includes transaction_id, message_id and other attribute keys that identify the source & destination of the message being sent through the API request or response;
Message- identifies the content of the message e.g. the search intent, catalog details, order details, etc.;
All APIs are asynchronous, i.e.:
request is sent from sender to recipient;
recipient acknowledges the request by sending an "ACK" (or "NACK" if they cannot validate the request);
recipient sends response through the callback for the corresponding request API e.g. /on_search callback for /search request;
recipient of callback (could be the original sender) acknowledges the response by sending an "ACK" (or "NACK" if they cannot validate the request);
Every request & response pair is identified by a transaction_id + unique message_id & the sender of a request is able to correlate the response to the request using the above;
Error block can be sent in sync (in response to request) or async (along with callback) mode and should have the following attribute keys: error.type, error.code (mapped tostandard error codes definedhere);
Transaction trail for a buyer is maintained through a unique transaction_id for the pre-order stage, i.e. /search, /select, /init, /confirm and post-order stage ie. /status, /cancel, /update, /track. However, considering that most buyer apps cache catalogs that are reused by multiple buyer apps, for providing a good buyer experience, a unique transaction_id is maintained for /select, /init & /confirm.
Unique id for an order on a network will be identified by the transaction_id & order id;
If a stale request or response is received, i.e. with timestamp earlier than similar request or response (identified by the transaction_id + message_id) that has already been processed, the recipient can send "NACK" with the error code "20002" (BNP) and "30022" (SNP);
Buyer apps with live search functionality can use the same transaction_id across the entire pre-order stage;
Swagger link ishere;
Signing & Verification of requests & responses
Signing & Verification of requests & responses
Key pairs, for signing & encryption, can be generated using any standard library e.g.libsodium,Bouncy Castle, etc.
Creating key pairs
create key pairs, for signing (ed25519) & encryption (X25519);
update base64 encoded public keys in registry;
utility to generate signing key pairs and test signing & verification ishere;
Auth Header Signing
generate UTF-8 byte array from json payload;
generate Blake2b hash from UTF-8 byte array;
create base64 encoding of Blake2b hash, this becomes the digest for signing;
sign the request, using your private signing key, and add the signature to the request authorization header, following steps documented here;
Auth Header Verification
extract the digest from the encoded signature in the request;
get the signing_public_key from registry using lookup (by using the ukId in the authorization header);
create (UTF-8) byte array from theraw payloadand generate Blake2b hash;
compare generated Blake2b hash with thedecoded digestfrom the signature in the request;
in case of failure to verify, HTTP error 401 should be thrown;
Registry lookup
There are 2 possible participant types, for each domain, in the ONDC registry:
Buyer NP
Seller NP
Seller NP could be either ISN (Inventory Seller Node) or MSN (Marketplace Seller Node or Aggregator)
Each participant type, defined above, will have an entry intheregistry for their entity. Every participant on the ONDC registry will have one or more entries in the registry, with unique identifier ("ukid") for each such entry;
All requests & responses have to be signed by the sender and verified by the receiver. If any request fails verification, it should be rejected (NACK’d) with http 401 error code;
The identity of the sender of a request is sent, through the auth header, as follows:
keyId="{subscriber_id}|{unique_key_id[a]}|{algorithm}"
BNP & SNP will use their private key for signing, for which the corresponding public key will be in the registry, for their "ukid";
Verification of requests using registry lookup usesthisAPI spec. Participants can either use the registry lookup endpoints fromhereor cache the registry locally (with refresh at regular intervals) for a local lookup;
Following options are available:
/v2.0/lookup
/v2.0/lookup
request:
{
"subscriber_id":"bnp.com",
"domain[1]":"ONDC:RET10",
"ukId":"UKID1",
"country[2]":"IND",
"city[3]":"std:080",
"type[4]":"BPP"
}
/v2.0/lookup supports secure access using Authorization headers. Steps to create Authorization header is mentioned in3.cabove.
Sample Curl:
curl --location 'https://prod.registry.ondc.org/v2.0/lookup' \
--header 'Content-Type: application/json' \
--header 'Authorization: Signature keyId="example-bap.com|bap1234|ed25519", algorithm="ed25519", created="<timestamp>", expires="<timestamp>", headers="(created)(expires)digest", signature="<signature>"' \
--data '{
"subscriber_id":"bnp.com",
"ukId":"UKID1"
}'
response:
(will be an array with 1 or more objects, depending on whether the entity, identified by the subscriber_id, has registered as different participants in a domain, e.g. BNP, SNP)
