Incremental catalog refresh
Incremental refresh is necessary for BNPs that cache catalogs and have to reflect changes since the lastfullcatalog refresh;
Incremental refresh willinclude:
item(s) changes - entire item record to be sent when there are delta changes since the last full catalog snapshot;
store temporarily closed for online orders;
store (i.e. provider location) disabling;
provider / merchant disabling;
Incremental refresh willnot include:
disabling & enabling of customization groups, custom menu, variants will be through the full catalog refresh;
new provider(s) / location(s);
Every BNP that wants to consume incremental catalog changes should send a /search request through the gateway, with following params:
mode- "start", "stop";
start_time- start time for incremental refresh;
end_time- end time for incremental refresh;
Following scenarios are possible:
BNP requests1-timeincremental refresh:
start_time<Context.timestamp,end_time<=Context.timestamp,end_time>start_time
means BNP pulls incremental updates fromstart_timetoend_timein a single solicited response;
response will have the same transaction_id & message_id as the request;
BNP requestsregularincremental refresh until stopped:
mode="start",start_time<=Context.timestamp(means SNP pushes incremental updates fromstart_timeat a frequency range of 1-30 mins). If no start_time provided, it defaults to Context.timestamp;
SNP should aggregate and push updates, at the same time, to all BNPs that have requested for incremental refresh;
each response will have the same transaction_id but different message_id;
if there are no incremental catalog updates, SNP should not send empty catalog;
Buyer NP requests stopping of incremental refresh:
mode="stop";
transaction_id for stop incremental search request should be same as start incremental search request;
All the above scenarios are mandatory for all NPs;
At any point of time, BNP may have only 1 open incremental search request (i.e. 1-time or regular):
Accordingly, BNP needs to stop the current incremental search request before initiating a new incremental search request:
To handle race condition where BNP receives full & incremental refresh at the same time:
to enable BNP to distinguish between full vs incremental catalog response, a custom response header should be used by SNPs:
"X-ONDC-Search-Response:inc" - for incremental response;
"X-ONDC-Search-Response:full" - for full response;
since incremental catalog changes are sent directly to BNP, the auth header will only have the signature of SNP (and not include the gateway signature in x-gateway-authorization);
versioning is enabled for both types of refresh:
full refresh will have a timestamp at the provider & location level and indicates when the snapshot was generated;
incremental refresh will have a timestamp at provider / location / item level and indicates the time of the event;
in case BNP receives full & incremental refresh at the same time, either of these approaches for processing is feasible:
BNP can process the full refresh and then initiate incremental refresh e.g. if full refresh at 8AM was ingested between 8-9AM, BNP can stop theincrementalrefresh before initiating thefullrefresh or choose to ignore allincrementalrefresh within this duration of catalog ingestion. After processing the full refresh, BNP can initiate incremental refresh based on the timestamp in full refresh;
BNP can process full & incremental refresh in sequence and use the timestamp to decide which incremental refresh updates to persist;
To handle error conditions:
BNP not responding or responding with a NACK:
SNP should push catalog updates in multiple incremental refresh until ACK is received from all BNPs[c][d]. Response format for NACK ishere;
BNP that didn’t request for incremental catalog changes should respond with NACK for all incremental catalog changes received;
In the sync ACK/NACK response to incremental catalog refresh, BNP can communicate whether the refresh was successfully ingested or not and the error codes & message format are definedhere;
